\title{
Refinancing and The Transmission of Monetary Policy to Consumption*
}

\author{
Arlene Wong ${ }^{\dagger}$
}

February, 2019

\begin{abstract}
This paper examines the role of refinancing channel and the mortgage market structure for the transmission of monetary policy to consumption. First, I document heterogeneous consumption responses to rate shocks. Consumption of younger people is more responsive and explains most of the aggregate response. The response is driven by homeowners who refinance or enter new loans, which is concentrated among younger people. Second, I develop a life-cycle model with fixed rate mortgages that explains these facts. In the model, the young are both more likely to refinance and, at the same time, be against their short-term liquidity constraints. This generates a covariance between the propensity to refinance and short-term liquidity constraints, which generates sizable cross-sectional and aggregate consumption responses to monetary policy shocks. The findings suggest that the refinancing channel and the mortgage market structure is important for the transmission of monetary policy.
\end{abstract}

Keywords: Consumption; monetary policy; refinancing; heterogeneous responses; age

